Powerful Data Project Part II: Drug testing

There is a lot of fuss about steroids! Many are proponents of using them right and many say that they can cause roid rage, which presents as agression, unpredictability and backne…almost like being really hungry teenager with a temper. But the question that a lot of lifters like me have asked themselves is:

Is taking steroids worth it?

My opinion is that this is a very personal decision that anyone interested in strength or physique needs to make on their own. In the lifting world you will rarely find someone who hasn’t had to make that decision at one point. Here’s how I made mine:

When I was a kid, just starting to lift more seriously to lose some weight. As many, I started with bodybuilding and managed to lose 100+ lbs. At one point I hit a wall. It had been about 2-3 years into lifting and I was getting pretty good results. However, I wasn’t improving as quickly anymore. I went to the owner of my hometown gym, long time family friend and also a former professional bodybuilder (now IFBB judge) and asked him if I should try anabolic steroids. I won’t give you too much detail, but he diswayed me from that idea rather quickly. He made his strongest argument with a question: “Will you ever make bodybuilding your career?”. I knew I wasn’t and that led me to think for a while about what steroids would do for me. For myself, the pros did not outweigh the cons, they didn’t even come close. So I never tried and I don’t think I ever will…unless they get legalized after the government finally allows scientists to analyze their effects on the human body.

Shameless plug for science: Restricting scientists from testing products that are used worldwide and impact many lives is a bit backwords Criminalizing steroid use is not stopping almost anybody from taking them and you will be surprised at the frequency of people, who don’t necessarily look it like it, but still take steroids by the perscription of the local gym guru. Don’t let Randy tell people what/how much/how often to take steroids…let scientists apply their methods and tell you what is “safe.”

MOVE IT ALONG, ELIAS…I know. Let’s get to the point of this article. Do steroids help you lift more weights??

The approach that I am taking here is the following: I will break down the dataset into two groups - lifters that compete in a federation that is drug tested and lifters that compete in a non-drug tested league. Several assumptions made here:

  • I will assume that drug tested federations only have drug-free athletes. This is definitely not always true. There have been lifters that admit to taking steroids, while they avoid detection, but that’s a deeper issue that this dataset is not equipped at getting at. And those lifters are likely fewer than the majority that just wants to compete in a drug-free federation.

  • I will assume that lifters in non-drug tested federations take steroids. This is definitely not always true, but there are a few reasons I am making this assumption: 1) If you weren’t taking steroids and you think steroids make people stronger, you should probably be competing in a drug tested federation because that just puts you in a disadvantage. 2) there are likely more lifters that take steroids in non-drug tested federations than the ones that don’t, so that will likely sway the data more to the mean of enhanced lifters.

Let’s take a look

Obviously this is a fantastic and well kept dataset! Great job Sean Stangl of openpowerlifting.com!

I want to draw your attention that there are so many columns in this dataset, each containing unique information about each lifter. This will give us a lot of power to draw some observations about patterns of skills and potentials of the lifters.

Let’s see how many leagues are represented and how frequently

#table(open2$Federation)
ord<-order(as.matrix(table(open2$Federation)),decreasing = TRUE)
feds<-as.matrix(table(open2$Federation))
length(feds[ord,])
## [1] 113

That’s pretty interesting, we have a good amount of federations (n=113). Now, openpowerlifting has included for us some fantastic data, so we can simply select drugtested vs. non-drug tested federation and compare the differences. I will first exclude any federation with less than 10 000 entries. I know this is a rather arbitrary number, but I want to only include data from fedrations that I know have good rule following in terms of accepted lifts and if they test, I want to know that the fedration does the testing properly. I can assume that those two criteria are more likely to be in fedrations that have large participation.

selectfeds<-filter(as.data.frame(table(open2$Federation)),Freq>10000)


open2_10k<-open2 %>%
  filter(Federation %in% selectfeds[,1])

drug<-open2_10k %>% 
  filter(Tested=="No")
natty<-open2_10k %>% 
  filter(Tested=="Yes")
dim(natty)[[1]]/dim(drug)[[1]]
## [1] 4.431114

Wow! What is really interesting is that there are about 4.5x more people competing in drug tested leagues than in non-drug tested leagues! Let’s look at a distribution of the number of events happening in the different equipment types.

equipd<-as.data.frame(table(drug$Equipment))
equipn<-as.data.frame(table(natty$Equipment))
equipd<-equipd[-4,]
equip<-cbind(equipd[,2],equipn[,2])
colnames(equip)<-c("drug","natty")
rownames(equip)<-equipd$Var1

equip_norm<-as.data.frame(cbind(as.factor(equipd$Var1),equip[,1]/sum(equip[,1]),equip[,2]/sum(equip[,2])))
equip_norm[,1]<-equipd$Var1
colnames(equip_norm)<-c("equipment","drug","natty")

equip2<-melt(equip_norm)
## Using equipment as id variables
ggplot(equip2,
       aes(x=equipment,y=value,color=variable))+
  geom_point(aes(cex=3))+
  theme_classic()

So interestingly, the only category in which natty lifters are more abundant (and by far) is the single ply. These are corrected as proportions of total lifters that are in “natty” or “drug” leagues. I think it’s about time to take a look at some weights. So I think the most informative category here would be to look at natty lifters. If you look proportionally, this is the moste equially distributed number, and also enough lifters to actually test some hypotheses.

raw<-open2_10k %>% 
  filter(Best3BenchKg>0 & Best3DeadliftKg>0 & Best3SquatKg>0) %>%
  filter(!is.na(Age)) %>%
  filter(Equipment=="Raw") %>% 
  select(Equipment,Age,BodyweightKg,Best3SquatKg,Best3BenchKg,Best3DeadliftKg,TotalKg,Wilks,Group,Federation,Tested,Sex)

ggplot(raw,
       aes(x=BodyweightKg,y=TotalKg,color=Tested))+
  geom_point(cex=.1)+
  facet_wrap(.~Sex)+
  theme_classic()
## Warning: Removed 181 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Hmm, there are no super-obvious differences that I can see here. Let’s plot the means and ranges of these two categories by weight and maybe we can start seeing some differences.

m_raw_quant<-raw %>%
  filter(Sex=="M") %>% 
  group_by(BodyweightKg,Tested) %>% 
  summarize(low_total=quantile(TotalKg,0.05,na.rm=T),
            med_total=quantile(TotalKg,0.5,na.rm=T),
            high_total=quantile(TotalKg,0.95,na.rm=T))

ggplot(m_raw_quant %>% filter(BodyweightKg<160&BodyweightKg>50),
       aes(x=BodyweightKg,fill=Tested,color=Tested))+
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin=low_total,ymax=high_total),alpha=.2,colour=NA)+
  geom_line(aes(y=med_total))+
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1")+
  theme_classic()

Well that is badass. I think we can clearly see some differences in here. Any red color above is lifters at that weight that are not drug tested, lifting more than tested lifters. Any time you see blue, tested lifters are lifting more than untested. At the top you have the top 5% of the distribution and at the bottom you have the bottom 5%. I’ve removed lifters under 50kg and above 160 because there is just not enough data to show any distribution.

The good news here: the median doesn’t seem to change. On average, tested and untested league lifters perform just about the same. At the high end, those top 5%, seem to perform a bit better. Is it worth it? How much better? Let’s just take a look at women for a bit and we will come back to it.

f_raw_quant<-raw %>%
  filter(Sex=="F") %>% 
  group_by(BodyweightKg,Tested) %>% 
  summarize(low_total=quantile(TotalKg,0.05,na.rm=T),
            med_total=quantile(TotalKg,0.5,na.rm=T),
            high_total=quantile(TotalKg,0.95,na.rm=T))

ggplot(f_raw_quant %>% filter(BodyweightKg<120&BodyweightKg>40),
       aes(x=BodyweightKg,fill=Tested,color=Tested))+
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin=low_total,ymax=high_total),alpha=.2,colour=NA)+
  geom_line(aes(y=med_total))+
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set1")+
  theme_classic()

I think with women we are stumbling upon a similar relationship, but not as pronounced as with men. Again, at the higher weights, tested lifters seem to perform better, but that could just be a factor of there being a lower number of representative lifters as well.

I think it’s time to take a look at how pronounced of an effect this is.

m_raw_drug<-m_raw_quant %>% 
  filter(Tested=="No")
m_raw_natty<-m_raw_quant %>% 
  filter(Tested=="Yes")
m_join<-inner_join(m_raw_drug,m_raw_natty,by="BodyweightKg")
male_diff<-m_join %>% 
  summarize(ldiff=low_total.x-low_total.y,
            mdiff=med_total.x-med_total.y,
            hdiff=high_total.x-high_total.y)


ggplot(male_diff %>% filter(BodyweightKg<160&BodyweightKg>50),
       aes(x=BodyweightKg))+
  geom_line(aes(y=mdiff),col="green")+
#  geom_line(aes(y=ldiff),col="red")+
  geom_line(aes(y=hdiff),col="orange")+
  theme_classic()

interp <- approx(male_diff$BodyweightKg, male_diff$hdiff, n=10000)
male_diff2 <- data.frame(BodyweightKg=interp$x, hdiff=interp$y)
male_diff2$col[male_diff2$hdiff >= 0] <- "Not-tested"
male_diff2$col[male_diff2$hdiff < 0] <- "Tested"

ggplot(male_diff2 %>% filter(BodyweightKg<160&BodyweightKg>50),
       aes(x=BodyweightKg,y=hdiff))+
  geom_area(aes(fill=col))+
  theme_classic()

#Repeating for median
interp <- approx(male_diff$BodyweightKg, male_diff$mdiff, n=10000)
male_diff2 <- data.frame(BodyweightKg=interp$x, hdiff=interp$y)
male_diff2$col[male_diff2$hdiff >= 0] <- "Not-tested"
male_diff2$col[male_diff2$hdiff < 0] <- "Tested"

ggplot(male_diff2 %>% filter(BodyweightKg<160&BodyweightKg>50),
